<html
  xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
  xmlns:tal="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/tal"
  xmlns:metal="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/metal"
  xmlns:i18n="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/i18n"
  xml:lang="en"
  lang="en"
  dir="ltr"
  metal:use-macro="context/@@main_template/master"
  i18n:domain="launchpad"
>

<body>

<metal:leftportlets fill-slot="portlets_one">
  <div tal:replace="structure context/@@+portlet-packages" />
  <div tal:replace="structure context/@@+portlet-milestones" />
</metal:leftportlets>

<metal:rightportlets fill-slot="portlets_two">
  <div tal:replace="structure context/@@+portlet-details" />
  <div tal:replace="structure context/product/@@+portlet-summary" />
</metal:rightportlets>

<metal:heading fill-slot="pageheading">
  <h1>Release series overview</h1>
</metal:heading>

<div metal:fill-slot="main">


  <div id="series-details">
    <p tal:content="context/summary">
        $ProductSeries.summary goes here. This should be quite short,
        just a single paragraph of text really, giving the status of
        this series of releases.
    </p>
    Status: <strong tal:content="context/status/title" />
  </div>

    <p>
      <img src="/@@/info" />
      A "release series" is major release that would typically have a number
      of "point releases" associated with it. For example, Mozilla Firefox
      series "1.5" has releases such as "1.5a1", "1.5b1", "1.5.0" and
      "1.5.2". In revision control terms, the best practice is to
      create a Bazaar branch for this specific series of releases.
    </p>

    <tal:has_releases condition="context/releases">

      <h2>Releases</h2>

      <div tal:replace="structure context/@@+table-releases" />

    </tal:has_releases>

    <h2>Code for this series</h2>

    <div tal:replace="structure context/@@+code-summary" />

</div>

</body>
</html>
